{{osm box|w|555300215}}
'''Kamigoryō Shrine''' ({{ill|Kamigoryō Shrine|ja|上御霊神社}}, Kamigoryō Jinja) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}} located in {{ill|Kamigyō-ku|ja|上京区}}, {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都市}}. The shrine's official name as a religious institution is simply "Goryō Shrine" (御靈神社), and it is classified as a former {{ill|Fusha|ja|府社}}. The name Kamigoryō ("Upper Goryō") Shrine contrasts with {{ill|Shimogoryō Shrine|ja|下御霊神社}}, the "Lower Goryō Shrine."

== History ==
The shrine's origins trace back to the reign of {{ill|Emperor Kanmu|ja|桓武天皇}}, when epidemics spread across the land. These outbreaks were attributed to the curses of {{ill|goryō spirits|ja|御霊信仰}}, and in {{ill|Enryaku|ja|延暦}} 13 (794 CE), the vengeful spirit of {{ill|Prince Sawara|ja|早良親王}} (posthumously deified as Sudō Tennō) was enshrined here. It is said that the shrine also served as the {{ill|guardian shrine|ja|鎮守社}} for the Izumo clan's temple, {{ill|Kamizumo Temple|ja|上出雲寺}}, which existed before the capital's relocation to Heian-kyō.

In {{ill|Jōgan|ja|貞観 (日本)}} 5 (863 CE), a {{ill|Goryō-e|ja|御霊会}} ritual was held at the {{ill|Shinsen-en|ja|神泉苑}} to appease six spirits, including Sudō Tennō. This event marked the foundation of both Kamigoryō Shrine and Shimogoryō Shrine.

Over the years, two additional deities, {{ill|Fire Thunder God|ja|火雷神}} and {{ill|Kibi no Makibi|ja|吉備真備}}, were added to the original six spirits. In the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代}}, Kamigoryō Shrine was known as "Kamizumoji Goryō-dō" (Upper Izumo Shrine) and enjoyed imperial patronage. By {{ill|Shitoku|ja|至徳 (日本)}} 1 (1384 CE), it was granted the Rank of {{ill|Shōichii|ja|正一位|1=Senior First Rank}}, the highest shrine Rank.

In {{ill|Bunshō|ja|文正 (日本)}} 2 (1467 CE), a conflict occurred at the shrine when {{ill|Hatakeyama Masanaga|ja|畠山政長}} clashed with {{ill|Hatakeyama Yoshinari|ja|畠山義就}}, an event known as the {{ill|Battle of Kamigoryō Shrine|ja|御霊合戦}}. This skirmish was the prelude to the {{ill|Ōnin War|ja|応仁の乱}}, earning the shrine the title "Birthplace of the Ōnin War."

The shrine has also been associated with the {{ill|Izumo-no-oi Shrine|ja|出雲井於神社}} and {{ill|Izumo Takano Shrine|ja|出雲高野神社}} listed in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho}}, though continuity is unclear.

During the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代}}, Kamigoryō Shrine was classified as a {{ill|Fusha|ja|府社}}.

== Deities ==
The shrine enshrines eight primary deities, known collectively as the "Eight Goryō Deities" (八所御霊):
* Sudō Tennō ({{ill|Prince Sawara|ja|早良親王}}, son of {{ill|Emperor Kōnin|ja|光仁天皇}})
* {{ill|Empress Dowager Inoue|ja|井上大皇后}} (wife of Emperor Kōnin)
* {{ill|Prince Iyo|ja|他戸親王}} (son of Emperor Kōnin)
* {{ill|Fujiwara no Yoshiko|ja|藤原吉子}} (mother of {{ill|Prince Iyo|ja|伊予親王|1=Iyo Shinnō}})
* {{ill|Tachibana no Hayanari|ja|橘逸勢}}
* {{ill|Funya no Miyatamaro|ja|文室宮田麻呂}}
* {{ill|Fire Thunder God|ja|火雷神}} (collective spirit of the six aforementioned deities)
* {{ill|Kibi no Makibi|ja|吉備真備}}

Five additional deities are enshrined in the auxiliary shrine:
* {{ill|Ogura Family Deities|ja|小倉一族}} (Ogura Jitsuoki, Ogura Koretsune, and others)
* Wako Myōjin ({{ill|Sugawara no Kazuko|ja|菅原和子}}, associated with Sugawara family)

== Cultural Significance ==
The shrine reflects the historical importance of {{ill|goryō beliefs|ja|御霊信仰}} in Heian Japan, commemorating those who suffered tragic deaths during political strife. It continues to serve as a religious and historical site, preserving the memory of Kyoto's turbulent history.

== External Links ==
* [http://www.kyoto-jinjacho.or.jp/shrine/02/004/index.html Official Website (Kyoto Shrine Association)]
* {{Wayback|url=http://homepage3.nifty.com/suehiro-mikosi/ |title=末廣神輿 上御霊神社 |date=20100217171901}}



